Tinder is one of the most popular dating applications. Even I have used it in my loneliness during freshman year of university. But I noticed a lot of mixed feelings surrounding the app among my fellow classmates. So I thought, "how many people actually see Tinder in a positive light?" To check that and whether Tinder actually helps people we can analyze the sentiments of Tinder's Google Play Store reviews. Although it weill only be Android user reviews being looked at, that should still be a significant number of people. My personaly theory is that the reviews will be neutral on average, but that's more of a hunch; anyways, I'll get started!

A stop word is a commonly used word (such as “the”, “a”, “an”, “in”) and what was downloaded above will be a source of words that will help our clean function to... well, clean... below

In [49]:
def clean(text):
    text = str(text).lower()
    text = re.sub('\[.*?\]', '', text)
    text = re.sub('https?://\S+|www\.\S+', '', text)
    text = re.sub('<.*?>+', '', text)
    text = re.sub('[%s]' % re.escape(string.punctuation), '', text)
    text = re.sub('\n', '', text)
    text = re.sub('\w*\d\w*', '', text)
    text = [word for word in text.split(' ') if word not in stopword] # checks for stopwords
    text=" ".join(text)
    text = [stemmer.stem(word) for word in text.split(' ')]
    text=" ".join(text)
    return text


data["content"] = data["content"].apply(clean) # uses the clean function on the content column

Now we'll use Valence Aware Dictionary for Sentiment Reasoning (VADER)'s polarity scores function to calculate, and the SentimentIntensityAnalyzer() function takes in a string and returns a dictionary of scores in each of four categories: negative, neutral, positive, compound. The code below only uses the first three of which only.

In [51]:
#nltk.download('vader_lexicon') #similar to before, commented out after unzipping
sentiments = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer() #takes 3 minutes on my local machine :(
data["Positive"] = [sentiments.polarity_scores(i)["pos"] for i in data["content"]] 
data["Negative"] = [sentiments.polarity_scores(i)["neg"] for i in data["content"]]
data["Neutral"] = [sentiments.polarity_scores(i)["neu"] for i in data["content"]]
d1 = data[["content", "Positive", "Negative", "Neutral"]] #creates a new dataframe with our calculated scores columns
print(d1.head())

Now using the Positive, Negative, and Neutral columns/attributes of the d1 dataframe the I made earlier, we can calculate an over all sentiment score of Tinder with Android users with the function below as well as graph how exactly each column's numbers compare to each other.

In [115]:
x = sum(d1["Positive"])
y = sum(d1["Negative"])
z = sum(d1["Neutral"])

def sentiment_score(a, b, c): # calculates overall sentiment score
    if (a>b) and (a>c):
        print("Positive 😊 ")
    elif (b>a) and (b>c):
        print("Negative 😠 ")
    else:
        print("Neutral 🙂 ")
        
sentiment_score(x, y, z)
print("\nPositive: ", x)
print("Negative: ", y)
print("Neutral: ", z, "\n")
print("Visualized: \n")

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])


ex = ['Positive', 'Negative', 'Neutral']
ey = [x,y,z]
plt.bar(ex[0],ey[0],color='g',edgecolor='black')
plt.bar(ex[1],ey[1],color='r',edgecolor='black')
plt.bar(ex[2],ey[2],color='b',edgecolor='black')

print('But the total average star rating is: ', round(avgscore,3))

But the total average star rating is:  2.996

Now these score/star ratings on first glance show us something a little different than the sentiment score! But I believe this graph to be less correct; why? Because this graph only takes into account what people feel they would rate the app rather than what their words say. The content of their reviews offer much more insight than what they feel the app is graded. The graph is also very misleading with the 1 star rating being the highest but that wouldn't consider the other reviews' weights. However, I do feel there is something to be said as to why the overall sentiment is Neutral just by looking at the star ratings. If you calculate the average of the star ratings, you can see that it pretty much averages out to be around 2.996 (just from looking at the 1 and 5 star ratings averaged out alone), which is a very neutral 3 star rating. Which lines up with the Sentiment Score!
